{
  "texts": [
    "Many microfossils retain their original material, such as mineralized shells or skeletal elements, rather than undergoing complete remineralization.",
    "Their often excellent preservation allows for detailed analysis of their morphology and chemical composition, offering a direct window into ancient life (Itaki et al. 2020).",
    "The process by which microscopic organisms are fossilised varies depending on the type of organism and the environmental conditions.",
    "For instance, calcareous microfossils like Foraminifera and coccoliths (a type of nannofossil) are typically well-preserved in (often shallow) marine environments, rich in calcium carbonate (Mattioli and Pittet 2002).",
    "Siliceous microfossils, such as diatoms and radiolarians, in contrast are more often preserved in deep water settings in which calcium carbonate is unstable, but where intricate silica skeletons can accumulate over geological timescales (Armstrong and Brasier 2013)."
  ]
}